                    This is the teaching layer. 
                    Without a curriculum spec, the app can generate valid exercises but still teach badly. It 
                    can overwhelm beginners, repeat the wrong things, or introduce jazz language in the 
                    wrong order. 
                    This document defines: 
                         •    what each level means 
                         •    what concepts belong at each level 
                         •    what should appear first 
                         •    what should be delayed 
                         •    how the app should progress over time 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    Practice Curriculum Specification 
                    1. Purpose 
                    The Practice Curriculum defines how the app should teach over time. 
                    It ensures that: 
                         •    beginners are not given advanced material too early 
                         •    intermediate users get increasing variety 
                         •    advanced users get enough complexity 
                         •    Guided Practice sessions follow a meaningful learning path 
                    This is not just a difficulty label system. 
                    It is a progression model. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    2. Core Curriculum Principle 
                    The curriculum must teach in this order: 
                         1.  orientation 
                         2.  control 
                         3.  harmonic awareness 
                         4.  resolution 
                         5.  phrasing 
                         6.  language 
                         7.  creative use 
                    That means: 
                         •    first learn where notes are 
                         •    then learn how chords work 
                         •    then learn how harmony moves 
                         •    then learn how to target important notes 
                         •    then learn how to shape phrases 
                         •    then learn jazz vocabulary 
                         •    then apply it creatively 
                    If you reverse that order, the app becomes confusing. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    3. Curriculum Levels 
                    The app should support three levels: 
                         •    Beginner 
                         •    Intermediate 
                         •    Advanced 
                    These should not just change note density. 
                    They must change: 
                         •    concept exposure 
                         •    exercise selection 
                         •    rhythm complexity 
                         •    harmonic complexity 
                         •    melodic expectations 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    4. Beginner Curriculum 
                    4.1 Beginner Goal 
                    The beginner level teaches: 
                         •    note familiarity 
                         •    scale fluency 
                         •    basic chord awareness 
                         •    simple harmonic movement 
                         •    strong-beat resolution 
                         •    basic phrasing 
                    A beginner should leave this stage able to: 
                         •    play scales and arpeggios in a controlled way 
                         •    recognize II–V–I as a basic jazz movement 
                         •    hear and play guide tones 
                         •    land on clear target tones 
                         •    play very simple musical phrases 
                    4.2 Beginner Priorities 
                    The app should prioritize: 
                         •    repetition 
                         •    consistency 
                         •    simple rhythms 
                         •    small note range 
                         •    strong tonal clarity 
                    The app should avoid: 
                         •    excessive variation 
                         •    dense chromaticism 
                         •    advanced syncopation 
                         •    theoretical overload 
                         •    long sessions with too many concept shifts 
                    4.3 Beginner Allowed Concepts 
                    Technical: 
                         •    major scale 
                         •    natural minor scale 
                         •    major pentatonic 
                         •    minor pentatonic 
                         •    basic chromatic familiarity only if specifically selected 
                         •    major triad 
                         •    minor triad 
                         •    major 7 
                         •    minor 7 
                         •    simple arpeggios 
                    Jazz: 
                         •    II–V–I basics 
                         •    guide tones 
                         •    target tones 
                         •    simple call and response 
                    Reading: 
                         •    simple sight reading in limited range 
                         •    quarter notes 
                         •    half notes 
                         •    simple eighth notes later in beginner 
                    4.4 Beginner Disallowed or Delayed Concepts 
                    Do not include by default: 
                         •    bebop lines 
                         •    enclosure patterns 
                         •    advanced voice leading 
                         •    complex motif development 
                         •    blues progression complexity 
                         •    rhythm changes 
                         •    advanced chromatic approach logic 
                         •    dense syncopation 
                         •    triplets 
                         •    dotted rhythm complexity unless explicitly enabled later 
                    4.5 Beginner Rhythm Rules 
                    Allowed by default: 
                         •    whole notes 
                         •    half notes 
                         •    quarter notes 
                    Optional later in beginner: 
                         •    simple eighth-note pairs 
                    Avoid: 
                         •    syncopated accents 
                         •    swing complexity as a rhythmic concept 
                         •    off-beat resolution unless simplified 
                    If swing is enabled for beginner, keep pitch logic simple. 
                    4.6 Beginner Melodic Rules 
                    Prefer: 
                         •    stepwise motion 
                         •    small intervals 
                         •    repeated motifs 
                         •    clear strong-beat chord tones 
                    Avoid: 
                         •    wide leaps 
                         •    fast direction changes 
                         •    jagged contour 
                         •    chromatic note density 
                    4.7 Beginner Session Emphasis 
                    A beginner Guided Practice session should mostly contain: 
                         •    warm-up scale work 
                         •    simple arpeggios 
                         •    harmony basics 
                         •    guide tones 
                         •    target tones 
                         •    simple call and response 
                    Suggested emphasis split: 
                         •    35% technique 
                         •    35% harmony 
                         •    20% simple jazz phrasing 
                         •    10% reading or creative response 
                    4.8 Beginner Progression Sequence 
                    The app should introduce beginner content in this order across repeated sessions: 
                    Stage B1 
                         •    major scale 
                         •    major triad 
                         •    simple sight reading 
                         •    simple call and response 
                    Stage B2 
                         •    natural minor scale 
                         •    minor triad 
                         •    major 7 / minor 7 arpeggio awareness 
                         •    simple II–V–I introduction 
                    Stage B3 
                         •    guide tones 
                         •    target tones 
                         •    stronger harmonic connection 
                         •    slightly larger range 
                    Stage B4 
                         •    simple phrase shaping 
                         •    slightly more rhythmic variety 
                         •    stronger session coherence 
                    A user does not need an account-based “level unlock” in v1, but the generator should 
                    still bias content in that order. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    5. Intermediate Curriculum 
                    5.1 Intermediate Goal 
                    The intermediate level teaches: 
                         •    stronger harmonic connection 
                         •    smoother voice leading 
                         •    more rhythmic flexibility 
                         •    motif awareness 
                         •    more varied phrasing 
                         •    first controlled chromatic ideas 
                    An intermediate user should be able to: 
                         •    follow progressions more clearly 
                         •    connect chord tones across changes 
                         •    play with more rhythmic movement 
                         •    recognize and develop short motifs 
                         •    begin using light jazz vocabulary beyond scales 
                    5.2 Intermediate Priorities 
                    The app should prioritize: 
                         •    harmonic connection over isolated drills 
                         •    phrase shape 
                         •    controlled variation 
                         •    modest chromaticism 
                         •    stronger progression awareness 
                    5.3 Intermediate Allowed Concepts 
                    Technical: 
                         •    all beginner material 
                         •    harmonic minor 
                         •    blues scale 
                         •    chromatic scale as a technical tool 
                         •    diminished and augmented triads as theory/drill material where appropriate 
                    Jazz: 
                         •    II–V–I in multiple keys 
                         •    guide tones 
                         •    target tones 
                         •    voice leading 
                         •    motif development 
                         •    call and response 
                         •    optional first bebop line exposure 
                         •    blues progression basics 
                         •    turnaround basics 
                    Reading: 
                         •    wider range 
                         •    eighth notes 
                         •    more mixed rhythm 
                         •    moderate leaps 
                         •    simple rests 
                    5.4 Intermediate Delayed Concepts 
                    Still limit: 
                         •    dense bebop language 
                         •    frequent enclosure use 
                         •    advanced substitutions 
                         •    rhythm changes as default material 
                         •    highly syncopated or triplet-heavy lines 
                         •    complex altered dominant language 
                    5.5 Intermediate Rhythm Rules 
                    Allowed: 
                         •    quarter notes 
                         •    eighth notes 
                         •    rests 
                         •    simple syncopation 
                         •    swing feel if enabled 
                         •    some dotted rhythm use if explicitly supported 
                    Avoid overuse of: 
                         •    triplets 
                         •    tied syncopation if not well implemented 
                         •    dense rhythmic clutter 
                    5.6 Intermediate Melodic Rules 
                    Prefer: 
                         •    a mix of stepwise motion and moderate leaps 
                         •    stronger phrase contour 
                         •    more clear approaches into targets 
                         •    motif reuse across measures 
                    Allow: 
                         •    occasional chromatic approaches 
                         •    recovery after leaps 
                         •    stronger beat/off-beat contrast 
                    5.7 Intermediate Session Emphasis 
                    A typical intermediate session should contain: 
                         •    one technical warm-up 
                         •    one harmonic drill 
                         •    one voice-leading or target-tone step 
                         •    one phrase-development step 
                         •    optional reading or creative application 
                    Suggested emphasis split: 
                         •    25% technique 
                         •    30% harmony 
                         •    30% jazz phrasing/language 
                         •    15% creative/reading 
                    5.8 Intermediate Progression Sequence 
                    Stage I1 
                         •    reinforce II–V–I in more keys 
                         •    stronger target-tone practice 
                         •    simple voice leading 
                    Stage I2 
                         •    motif development 
                         •    rhythm variation 
                         •    wider phrase shapes 
                    Stage I3 
                         •    first chromatic approach tones 
                         •    blues progression basics 
                         •    more connected melodic lines 
                    Stage I4 
                         •    occasional bebop entry 
                         •    longer jazz-focus steps 
                         •    stronger creative application 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    6. Advanced Curriculum 
                    6.1 Advanced Goal 
                    The advanced level teaches: 
                         •    fluid harmonic outlining 
                         •    stronger jazz vocabulary 
                         •    chromatic approach logic 
                         •    phrase design 
                         •    variation and development 
                         •    higher cognitive flexibility 
                    An advanced user should be able to: 
                         •    practice over progressions with clarity 
                         •    connect harmony through voice leading 
                         •    use chromatic approaches intentionally 
                         •    develop motifs across changes 
                         •    move between technical and expressive work smoothly 
                    6.2 Advanced Priorities 
                    The app should prioritize: 
                         •    harmonic sophistication 
                         •    phrase quality 
                         •    variation without randomness 
                         •    chromatic control 
                         •    key fluency 
                         •    musical continuity 
                    6.3 Advanced Allowed Concepts 
                    Technical: 
                         •    all scale and chord materials 
                         •    full range practice 
                         •    chromatic drills 
                         •    more complex arpeggio shapes 
                    Jazz: 
                         •    all prior modes 
                         •    bebop lines 
                         •    advanced voice leading 
                         •    motif development with more transformation 
                         •    stronger call and response 
                         •    blues progression 
                         •    turnaround practice 
                         •    more frequent guide-tone and target-tone integration 
                    Reading: 
                         •    wider ranges 
                         •    denser rhythms 
                         •    stronger contour changes 
                         •    more mixed difficulty 
                    6.4 Advanced Still Needs Restraint 
                    Do not assume advanced means chaotic. 
                    Still avoid: 
                         •    meaningless complexity 
                         •    chromatic overload 
                         •    constant large leaps 
                         •    every exercise being maximally dense 
                    Advanced should mean more intentional, not just harder. 
                    6.5 Advanced Rhythm Rules 
                    Allowed: 
                         •    swing eighth feel 
                         •    syncopation 
                         •    denser eighth-note lines 
                         •    dotted patterns if implemented well 
                         •    more varied rhythmic templates 
                    Future expansion later: 
                         •    triplets 
                         •    tied anticipations 
                         •    more advanced rhythmic displacement 
                    6.6 Advanced Melodic Rules 
                    Allow: 
                         •    wider contour 
                         •    more phrase contrast 
                         •    enclosure patterns 
                         •    stronger approach-note logic 
                         •    richer target-tone placement 
                         •    more fluid continuity across measures 
                    Still enforce: 
                         •    harmonic clarity 
                         •    phrase coherence 
                         •    range awareness 
                    6.7 Advanced Session Emphasis 
                    Suggested emphasis split: 
                         •    15% technique 
                         •    25% harmony 
                         •    40% jazz language and phrase work 
                         •    20% creative/reading 
                    Advanced sessions should feel less like drills and more like applied musical practice. 
                    6.8 Advanced Progression Sequence 
                    Stage A1 
                         •    stronger voice leading 
                         •    more key rotation 
                         •    more target-tone variety 
                    Stage A2 
                         •    bebop line entry 
                         •    chromatic approaches 
                         •    motif transformation 
                    Stage A3 
                         •    more progression variety 
                         •    blues and turnaround reinforcement 
                         •    richer rhythmic patterns 
                    Stage A4 
                         •    integrated sessions with stronger creative focus 
                         •    more expressive closing exercises 
                         •    less dependence on purely technical warm-up 
                                                                                                                                                 
