              8. Guided Practice Curriculum Rules 
              Guided Practice should reflect level-specific teaching priorities. 
              Beginner Guided Practice Rules 
                 •   same key across whole session 
                 •   mostly one concept per step 
                 •   more repetition across days 
                 •   strong preference for scales, arpeggios, guide tones 
                 •   creative step should remain simple 
                    Intermediate Guided Practice Rules 
                         •    same key across whole session 
                         •    stronger mode variation 
                         •    progression awareness stronger 
                         •    motif and voice-leading steps appear regularly 
                         •    reading may be more active 
                    Advanced Guided Practice Rules 
                         •    same key by default, mixed key later if added 
                         •    more varied session focus across days 
                         •    bebop and chromatic language can appear 
                         •    creative application should be more prominent 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    9. Day-to-Day Rotation Rules 
                    The curriculum should not only define level, but also weekly variation. 
                    Beginner weekly rhythm 
                    A beginner should see more repetition. 
                    Suggested weekly pattern: 
                         •    Day 1: scales + arpeggios + guide tones 
                         •    Day 2: scales + II–V–I + target tones 
                         •    Day 3: review / simple reading 
                         •    Day 4: scales + arpeggios + call and response 
                         •    Day 5: II–V–I + guide tones 
                         •    Day 6: lighter review 
                         •    Day 7: mixed beginner recap 
                    Intermediate weekly rhythm 
                    More varied: 
                         •    one harmony-heavy day 
                         •    one phrase-heavy day 
                         •    one reading-heavy day 
                         •    one motif/creative day 
                         •    one integrated day 
                         •    one review day 
                         •    one lighter rotation day 
                    Advanced weekly rhythm 
                    Can rotate emphasis by focus: 
                         •    voice leading day 
                         •    bebop language day 
                         •    progression day 
                         •    creative phrasing day 
                         •    reading/integration day 
                         •    blues/turnaround day 
                         •    mixed advanced day 
                    This does not need full calendar implementation in v1, but the generator should be 
                    designed so it can support day emphasis later. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    10. Difficulty Mapping Rules 
                    Difficulty labels should map to actual behavior. 
                    Beginner means: 
                         •    limited note values 
                         •    limited concept set 
                         •    limited phrase length 
                         •    high clarity 
                         •    high repetition 
                    Intermediate means: 
                         •    broader concept set 
                         •    moderate variation 
                         •    stronger phrase movement 
                         •    moderate chromaticism 
                    Advanced means: 
                         •    richer vocabulary 
                         •    more varied contours 
                         •    more complex rhythm 
                         •    more integration between concepts 
                    Never define difficulty by tempo alone. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    11. Curriculum Guardrails 
                    These are strict rules to prevent bad teaching. 
                    Rule 1 
                    Do not introduce more than one new musical concept in the same beginner session. 
                    Rule 2 
                    Do not place the most complex concept in the first step. 
                    Rule 3 
                    Do not let creative exercises become theory-heavy explanations. 
                    Rule 4 
                    Do not overuse bebop content at intermediate level. 
                    Rule 5 
                    Do not let advanced sessions become random complexity generators. 
                    Rule 6 
                    Always reinforce harmonic hearing before melodic decoration. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    12. Explanation Text by Level 
                    The same concept may need different explanation depth. 
                    Beginner explanation style 
                         •    very short 
                         •    concrete 
                         •    practical 
                         •    minimal jargon 
                    Example: 
                    “Guide tones are the notes that help define each chord. Play slowly and listen to how 
                    the harmony changes.” 
                    Intermediate explanation style 
                         •    still short 
                         •    may include basic theory names 
                         •    more emphasis on connection 
                    Example: 
                    “Guide tones are the 3rd and 7th of a chord. They help you hear how chords move from 
                    one to the next.” 
                    Advanced explanation style 
                         •    concise 
                         •    assumes some theory familiarity 
                         •    more focus on application 
                    Example: 
                    “Use this line to hear and practice guide-tone voice leading through the progression.” 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    13. Range Curriculum Rules 
                    Difficulty should also affect range. 
                    Beginner 
                         •    narrower range 
                         •    avoid extremes 
                         •    avoid frequent top/bottom boundary notes 
                    Intermediate 
                         •    moderate range expansion 
                         •    more movement across register 
                    Advanced 
                         •    fuller use of selected range 
                         •    more freedom, but still musically controlled 
                    This matters a lot for harmonica practice. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    14. Rhythm Curriculum Rules 
                    Beginner 
                         •    stable pulse 
                         •    simple durations 
                         •    minimal syncopation 
                    Intermediate 
                         •    more eighth-note movement 
                         •    occasional rests 
                         •    moderate syncopation 
                    Advanced 
                         •    swing and syncopation if enabled 
                         •    denser phrase rhythm 
                         •    more contrast 
                    Do not let rhythm complexity outrun harmonic understanding. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    15. Creative Curriculum Rules 
                    Creative phases should also scale. 
                    Beginner creative work 
                         •    simple call and response 
                         •    simple phrase echo 
                         •    target-tone awareness 
                    Intermediate creative work 
                         •    motif variation 
                         •    stronger phrase shape 
                         •    more deliberate response logic 
                    Advanced creative work 
                         •    phrase development across harmony 
                         •    more flexible target placement 
                         •    richer call/response logic 
                         •    more integrated jazz language 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    16. Reading Curriculum Rules 
                    Reading should support, not dominate. 
                    Beginner 
                         •    short, simple, tonal reading 
                         •    narrow range 
                         •    mostly quarter/half notes 
                    Intermediate 
                         •    moderate phrase reading 
                         •    broader range 
                         •    more eighth notes 
                    Advanced 
                         •    more varied reading 
                         •    denser rhythm 
                         •    stronger contour and harmonic awareness 
                    Reading should be easier than improvisational language work at the same level unless 
                    user explicitly chooses a reading focus. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    17. Curriculum Metadata for the Generator 
                    The developer should encode level rules as structured metadata. 
                    Example: 
                    type CurriculumProfile = { 
                      allowedModes: PracticeMode[]; 
                      disallowedModes: PracticeMode[]; 
                      preferredModesByPhase: Record<string, PracticeMode[]>; 
                      rhythmComplexity: "low" | "medium" | "high"; 
                      chromaticism: "none" | "light" | "moderate"; 
                      rangeUsage: "narrow" | "moderate" | "full"; 
                      repetitionBias: "high" | "medium" | "low"; 
                    }; 
                    Suggested profiles: 
                    Beginner 
                         •    rhythmComplexity: low 
                         •    chromaticism: none 
                         •    rangeUsage: narrow 
                         •    repetitionBias: high 
                    Intermediate 
                         •    rhythmComplexity: medium 
                         •    chromaticism: light 
                         •    rangeUsage: moderate 
                         •    repetitionBias: medium 
                    Advanced 
                         •    rhythmComplexity: high 
                         •    chromaticism: moderate 
                         •    rangeUsage: full 
                         •    repetitionBias: low 
                    This should drive generation behavior. 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    18. Acceptance Criteria 
                    The curriculum spec is successfully implemented when: 
                    Beginner sessions 
                         •    feel clear and repetitive enough 
                         •    avoid advanced concepts 
                         •    reinforce fundamentals 
                         •    use simple rhythm and narrow range 
                    Intermediate sessions 
                         •    introduce more variety 
                         •    use voice leading and motif work 
                         •    begin light chromaticism carefully 
                    Advanced sessions 
                         •    feel musically richer 
                         •    include stronger jazz language 
                         •    maintain coherence, not chaos 
                    Across all levels 
                         •    concepts appear in the right order 
                         •    same concept is explained appropriately by level 
                         •    generated sessions feel educational, not random 
                                                                                                                                                 
                    19. Final Instruction to the Developer 
                    Implement the curriculum as a teaching progression, not just a difficulty switch. Each 
                    level must define what concepts are allowed, what concepts are delayed, how much 
                    rhythmic and melodic complexity is acceptable, and how much repetition is needed. 
                    Beginner content must emphasize control and clarity, intermediate content must build 
                    connection and variation, and advanced content must emphasize musical fluency and 
                    richer jazz language. The curriculum should shape both exercise selection and 
                    generation behavior. 
                     
                     
